ervations of Pharaonic monuments, sculptures, and mummies. An early and ardent champion of archaeological conservation, ʿAbd al-Laṭīf condemns the vandalism wrought by tomb-robbers and notes with distaste that Egyptian grocers price their goods with labels written on recycled mummy-wrappings.The book’s second half relates his horrific eyewitness account of the great famine that afflicted Egypt in the years 597–598/1200–1202. ʿAbd al-Laṭīf was a keen observer of humanity, and he offers vivid first-hand depictions of starvation, cannibalism, and a society in moral free-fall.A Physician on the Nile contains great diversity in a small compass, distinguished by the acute, humane, and ever-curious mind of its author. It is rare to be able to hear the voice of such a man responding so directly to novelty, beauty, and tragedy.A bilingual Arabic-English edition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aFamineszEgyptxHistoryy13th century. 0aNatural historyzEgyptvPre-Linnean works. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh  aMuwaffaq al-Dīn Muḥammad ʿAbd al-Laṭīf ibn Yūsuf al-Baghdādī.  aancient Egyptian literature.  aancient Egyptian writing translated.  aancient Egyptian writing translation english.  aancient Egyptian writing.  aancient literature books.  aarabic literature books.  aarabic literature in english.  abook on ancient civilization.  abook on ancient cultures.  abooks on ancient Egypt.  aclassic arabic literature books.1 aKennedy, Philip F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMackintosh-Smith, Tim, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479806256.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479806256423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479806256/original  aEBA_BACKALL